_number as the center (if possible). Defaults to 100."}, "read": {"type": "async_function", "description": "Read the whole content of a file. Using absolute paths as the argument for specifying the file location.", "signature": "(self, path: str) -> metagpt.tools.libs.editor.FileBlock", "parameters": ""}, "scroll_down": {"type": "function", "description": "Moves the window down by 100 lines.", "signature": "(self) -> str", "parameters": ""}, "scroll_up": {"type": "function", "description": "Moves the window up by 100 lines.", "signature": "(self) -> str", "parameters": ""}, "search_dir": {"type": "function", "description": "Searches for search_term in all files in dir. If dir is not provided, searches in the current directory. ", "signature": "(self, search_term: str, dir_path: str = \'./\') -> str", "parameters": "Args: search_term: str: The term to search for. dir_path: str: The path to the directory to search."}, "search_file": {"type": "function", "description": "Searches for search_term in file. If file is not provided, searches in the current open file. ", "signature": "(self, search_term: str, file_path: Optional[str] = None) -> str", "parameters": "Args: search_term: str: The term to search for. file_path: str | None: The path to the file to search."}, "similarity_search": {"type": "async_function", "description": "staticmethod(function) -> method Convert a function to be a static method. A static method does not receive an implicit first argument. To declare a static method, use this idiom: class C: @staticmethod def f(arg1, arg2, ...): ... It can be called either on the class (e.g. C.f()) or on an instance (e.g. C().f()). Both the class and the instance are ignored, and neither is passed implicitly as the first argument to the method. Static methods in Python are similar to those found in Java or C++. For a more advanced concept, see the classmethod builtin.", "signature": "(query: str, path: Union[str, pathlib.Path]) -> List[str]", "parameters": ""}, "wri